provisions.content:
(1) In order to discharge his duties, a administrator shall, inter alia, have the power to:

(a) represent the debtor and manage the debtor’s business for the purposes of the
insolvency proceedings;

(b) receive the debtor’s mail and any electronic communications addressed to the
debtor with the exception of mail and communications which are manifestly of a
private nature;

(c) carry on the business of the debtor, but only to the extent necessary to fulfill the
objectives of the insolvency proceedings;

(d) receive all assets of the estate, including the books and records of the debtor;

(e) collect and include in the estate any amounts remaining unpaid with respect to
the issued share capital of a debtor or contributions to the debtor by partners;

(f) use and deal with the assets of the estate, including by selling any such asset
free of any security rights, encumbrances and liens;

(g) represent the debtor in any court proceedings in which the debtor is a party;

(h) prepare the list of claims;

(i) permit a creditor to sell an asset which is the object of a security right held by the
creditor for a claim, and to apply the relevant proceeds of the sale in satisfaction
of the creditor’s claim;

(j) separately maintain assets which are burdensome for the estate;

(k) apply to the court to examine any person on questions pertaining to the debtor’s
business;

(l) terminate, cancel or avoid, in accordance with this and other laws, and including
by application to the court, any transaction, contract, agreement or transfer to
which the debtor is a party;

(m) convene and organize the meetings of creditors as provided for in this Law;

(n) prepare and propose a plan of compromise, where appropriate;

(o) employ the services of agents and professionals to assist in the performance of
his duties; and

(p) do any and all other things necessary to the performance of his duties and which
are consistent with the objectives of the insolvency proceedings.

(2) The Minister of Justice may issue regulations to supplement the provisions in paragraph
(1) regarding the administrator’s powers.

The following claims shall not be admissible in insolvency proceedings:

(1) interest accruing on claims from the date of the opening of the insolvency proceedings;

(2) costs incurred by creditors by reason of their participation in the insolvency proceedings;

(3) fines, administrative penalties and other incidental legal consequences of a criminal or
administrative offence which obliges the debtor to pay;

(4) claims for which no consideration was owed by the debtor in return;

(5) claims for the repayment of a loan made to the debtor by a person holding directly or
indirectly not less than ten percent (10%) of the equity capital of the debtor, or recourse
claims against the debtor for a loan guaranteed or secured, or caused to be guaranteed
or secured, by such a person. If the debtor is a partnership, the claims in this paragraph
shall apply only when all general partners of the debtor are companies;

(6) claims for recourse which co-debtors or guarantors may have against the debtor if they
satisfy a creditor’s claim;

(7) claims for which the proofs of claim were filed after the deadline established for the filing
of proofs of claims;

(8) subordination of claims for which ineffective in insolvency proceedings has been agreed
between the creditor and the debtor; and

(9) interest on claims of the aforementioned kind.

(1) All proofs of claims shall be submitted in writing by creditors to the administrator by the
determined deadline.

(2) Each proof of claim shall contain the following information:

(a) the legal nature and cause of the claim;

(b) the time when the claim arose;

(c) the amount of the claim;

(d) any priority that may attach to the claim under Article 57;

(e) the nature and rank of any alleged security in any asset of the debtor and details
of the asset in which the alleged security exists; and

(f) copies of documents and other evidence in support of the above, if any.

(3) The administrator shall assist creditors in observing the required formalities.

The creditors’ meeting may consider and take decisions on any matter pertaining to the
insolvency proceedings, including:

(1) obtaining and considering a report from the administrator on the status of the insolvency
proceedings;

(2) the preparation, including by the administrator, of a plan of compromise;

(3) the approval of a plan of compromise;

(4) a decision to apply to the court to terminate the operating of the business of the debtor
and to proceed with a liquidation of the estate;

(5) the discharge and replacement of the administrator;

(6) the making of a proposal to the Minister of Justice regarding the amount of the
administrator’s remuneration;

(7) the appointment of a creditors’ committee; and

(8) any recommendations from the creditors’ committee.
